tion":["per 1 pieces","970 kJ \/ 232 kcal","6.3 g","26.3 g","11.3 g"],"hintsAndTricks":["We like to use strong or extra mature cheddar. For children, use medium or mild cheddar.","When using a biscuit cutter on scone dough, do not twist it or your scones will rise unevenly. Just press straight down and lift straight up, shaking cutter to loosen dough if necessary.","Best eaten same day. If you have any extras, they freeze well. Freeze on day of baking once completely cool.","Triangular scones are traditional in Scotland - cut the flattened dough into triangles with a knife instead of using a round pastry cutter.","Rough cheese scones - instead of patting dough flat and cutting out shapes, drop spoonfuls of dough onto baking tray straight from mixing bowl. The scones will bake with a rough look and a crispy outside with lots of flavour.","Scones are traditional throughout Britain and Ireland. They are quick to make anytime, and plain or fruited scones are popular for afternoon tea. These cheese scones are delicious with soups - make the scones and put them in the oven, and while they bake you can make a soup in your Thermomix."],"basicInfo":["easy","10m","20m","14 pieces"]}